Memory Leak:
        ->Objects which are no longer required and present in Heap, but Garbage Collector
          unable to remove them
        ->Example : Objects are referenced but unused

Most common causes of memory leaks:
        ->Excessive use of static members
          => In Java, static members (variables and methods) are generally not garbage collected
             until their corresponding class is unloaded. In most typical Java applications,
             classes remain loaded for the entire duration of the application's execution,
             meaning static members effectively persist until the application terminates
        ->Unclosed Resources
        ->Improper equals and hashcode implementation
        ->Excessive session creation/ objects creation
        ->Poorly written custom data structure

How to Prevent Memory Leaks:
       ->Avoid use of static members because they live for the entire life of the application
         , by default so it is better to set the reference to null, explicitly.
       ->Unclosed Resources: Wrap database connections, file streams, and network sockets
         in a try-with-resources block to ensure they are closed automatically.
       ->ThreadLocals: Always call ThreadLocal.remove() in a finally block to prevent data
         from lingering on threads that are reused in a thread pool.
       ->Listeners/Callbacks: Explicitly unregister event listeners or observers once the
         observing object is no longer active.Equals/HashCode: Ensure equals() and hashCode()
         are properly overridden for custom classes used as keys in hash-based collections
         to avoid duplicate entries
       ->Avoid String concatenation use StringBuilder

How to find memory leaks:
       ->Using tool VisualVm (comes with JDK)
       ->Eclipse Memory Analyzer (MAT)


